      • addPriority

        @Nonnull
T addPriority(@Nullable
                       Comparable<?> priority)
        Returns a copy of this object by adding a priority relative to other selected PLUS loans in the academic year. PLUS loans will be added to the package in ascending priority order. PLUS loans with no given priority are added last. Tie-breakers are (i) the start date of the earliest term for which the loan is selected and (ii) the position the loan appears in the selection list. In summary, if two loans have the same/no given priority the one appearing first considering (i) and then (ii) is packaged first. By adding several priorities to one given loan scripts associate a queue of priorities to that loan, in the sense that the first priority to be compared is the one added first and so on. Scripts must add priorities to loans in a consistent manner so that not ever should the system attempt to compare incomparable types.
        Parameters:
        priority - the priority. Null values are always assumed to come last.
        Returns:
        the copy with the added priority.

      • addReversedPriority

        @Nonnull
T addReversedPriority(@Nullable
                               Comparable<?> priority)
        Returns a copy of this object by adding a priority relative to other selected PLUS loans in the academic year. See addPriority(Comparable). The priority order in this case, however, will be the reversed, i.e. a descending priority order. PLUS loans with no given respective priority will still be added last.
        Parameters:
        priority - the priority. Null values are always assumed to come last.
        Returns:
        the copy with the added priority.

      • addPriority

        @Nonnull
<U> T addPriority(@Nonnull
                           Comparator<? super U> comparator,
                           @Nullable
                           U priority)
        Returns a copy of this object by adding a priority relative to other selected PLUS loans in the academic year. See addPriority(Comparable). The priority order in this case, however, will be given by an explicit comparator. PLUS loans with no given respective priority will still be added last.
        Parameters:
        comparator - the comparator.
        priority - the priority.
        Returns:
        the copy with the added priority.

      • withNoPriority

        @Nonnull
T withNoPriority()
        Returns a copy of this object with no priority queue relative to other s elected PLUS loans in the academic year. This should be called if the script wants to override the default prioritization established in the plusLoans binding.
        Returns:
        the copy with no priority.
